---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Architecture — P2P, signaling & relay — idr.to">
  <Header slot="header" />
  <Footer slot="footer" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Control vs data plane</p>
      <h1>P2P in detail: signaling vs data</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        idr.to is deliberately split: our hosted service knows <em>who</em> may talk to <em>whom</em> and helps
        peers find a network path. Once connected, your SSH sessions, SQL queries, and LLM API calls flow directly
        between devices whenever ICE succeeds.
      </p>

      <h2>What goes through idr.to servers</h2>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Registry &amp; policy</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Entity and device registration</li>
            <li>Host-Identity → Device-ID mappings</li>
            <li>ACL evaluation at <code>POST /resolve</code></li>
            <li>OIDC login, Signed Host-Identity, billing entitlements</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Signaling (WebSocket)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Target agents: persistent <code>wss://idr.to/v1/signal</code></li>
            <li>Sources: ephemeral WSS after resolve</li>
            <li>SDP offers/answers and ICE candidates relayed</li>
            <li>STUN URLs issued; TURN credentials when subscribed</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        Signaling messages are small JSON frames — kilobytes per connection setup, not your application throughput.
      </div>

      <h2>What stays peer-to-peer (default)</h2>
      <p>
        After ICE completes, peers run <strong>idr-tunnel-v1</strong>: a multiplexed layer-4 tunnel over a WebRTC
        data channel. Each stream maps to a TCP connection (or UDP-style datagrams when using <code>…UDP</code> port segments).
      </p>
      <pre class="flow-diagram">Source client                    idr.to API              Target agent (on-prem)
     |                                |                         |
     |-- POST /resolve -------------->|                         |
     |<-- device_id, signal_session --|                         |
     |                                |                         |
     |-- WSS signal.offer ------------------------------------>|
     |<-- WSS signal.answer -------------------------------------|
     |<======== ICE candidates (via WSS) =======================>|
     |                                                          |
     |======== WebRTC DATA (SSH/HTTP/Ollama bytes) =============>| local :11434
     |                                X                         |
     |                     (no app bytes on server)               |</pre>

      <h2>Agent modes</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Mode</th><th>Role</th><th>Typical deployment</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>source</strong></td><td>Initiates connections only</td><td>Developer laptop with SSH ProxyCommand</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>target</strong></td><td>Accepts inbound tunnels</td><td>Mac Mini in office running Ollama</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>hybrid</strong></td><td>Both</td><td>Edge gateway, CI runner</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>When P2P is not enough</h2>

      <h3>TURN relay (symmetric NAT / strict firewalls)</h3>
      <p>
        If ICE cannot establish a direct UDP path, peers may use <code>turn.idr.to</code> to relay WebRTC media.
        Traffic still uses WebRTC encryption; bytes pass through TURN infrastructure and <strong>count toward your data transfer bundles</strong>.
      </p>

      <h3>HTTPS edge relay (non-WebRTC clients)</h3>
      <p>
        Some clients only speak ordinary HTTPS/TLS to a public hostname — legacy integrations, certain corporate proxies,
        or tools that cannot load WebRTC. The open-source <strong>https-relay</strong> deploys on <code>*.idr.to</code>
        DEF hostnames:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Client connects to <code>https://&lt;def-label&gt;.idr.to/443/…</code></li>
        <li>Relay reads TLS SNI and DEF-decodes the Host-Identity</li>
        <li>Encrypted bytes pipe over agent WebSocket mux to on-prem service</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="callout callout--warn">
        <strong>Relay incurs data transfer charges.</strong> Relay bytes are metered in 500 GB bundles (US$10 each).
        Without purchased bundles, targets remain reachable on <strong>P2P connections only</strong> — signaling still works,
        but TURN and HTTPS relay paths are not provisioned.
      </div>

      <h2>Data transfer billing</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Bundles: <strong>500 GB</strong> increments at <strong>US$10</strong> each</li>
        <li>Subscribe to as many bundles as needed (stackable)</li>
        <li><strong>Unused data rolls over</strong> month-to-month for up to <strong>12 months</strong></li>
        <li>Applies to TURN and HTTPS relay mux metering</li>
        <li>Pure P2P (no relay) → <strong>no data charges</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p><a href="/pricing">See pricing →</a></p>

      <h2>Security properties</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Host-Identity</strong> — <code>host~entity-id</code>: entity-id is globally unique; host is unique within the entity; together globally addressable. DEF encoding → FQHN for DNS routing.</li>
        <li><strong>Device-ID</strong> — 120-bit routing address derived from on-device Ed25519 public key (first 120 bits of SHA-256); analogous to IP in IP-based routing</li>
        <li>Same-entity access allowed by default; cross-entity requires explicit ACL rows</li>
        <li><strong>TLS pass-through</strong> — HTTPS relay on port 443 reads SNI only and pipes ciphertext to the target agent; idr.to never terminates customer TLS in default mode</li>
        <li><strong>Let's Encrypt on target</strong> — ACME HTTP-01 via relay challenges; certificate and private key PEM files written locally on the edge device and renewed automatically — never uploaded to idr.to</li>
        <li>Browser SDK: credentials never touch ISV JavaScript — auth panel runs in SDK shadow DOM; resolve uses Signed Host-Identity + proof of possession</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>TLS &amp; certificates (detailed)</h2>
      <pre class="flow-diagram">Browser / curl                    https-relay (optional)              Target device
     │                                      │                              │
     │──── TLS ClientHello (SNI=DEF FQHN) ─►│                              │
     │                                      │── encrypted records ────────►│ nginx / app
     │                                      │   (pass-through)             │ LE cert + private key
     │◄────────────── TLS ServerHello ──────│◄─────────────────────────────│ (generated on device)
     │                                      │                              │
     │  idr.to never holds private keys     │  Relay sees ciphertext only  │  acme_agent renews via WSS</pre>
      <p>
        For P2P paths, TLS runs inside the WebRTC tunnel — still end-to-end between your client and the service on
        loopback. Whether P2P or relay, application plaintext is not available to idr.to infrastructure.
      </p>

      <h2>IPv6 and dual-stack</h2>
      <p>
        idr.to is not limited to IPv4. ICE gathers both address families when the OS provides them; P2P succeeds
        over IPv6 when both peers and the path support it. TURN and the optional HTTPS relay require
        <strong>A and AAAA</strong> DNS and open firewall ports on both stacks for production.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>IPv6-only networks</strong> often need TURN (or TURN over TCP/TLS) to reach IPv4-only peers or relays.</li>
        <li><strong>Tunnel OPEN</strong> targets a service on the remote device — default <code>127.0.0.1</code> is loopback on that machine, not your browser. Services on <code>::1</code> only need <code>openStream('::1', port)</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>HTTPS relay</strong> uses DEF hostnames in SNI, not IP literals; publish wildcard A/AAAA for <code>*.idr.to</code>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Also documented on this site</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/signaling">Signaling protocol</a></li>
        <li><a href="/addressing">Addressing &amp; URI grammar</a></li>
        <li><a href="/billing">Billing &amp; entitlements</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/blob/main/docs/TUNNEL.md">idr-tunnel-v1 wire format</a> (client repo)</li>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/blob/main/docs/AGENT_MODES.md">Agent modes</a> (client repo)</li>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/blob/main/docs/LOCAL_PROXY.md">Local proxy (SSH/SOCKS)</a> (client repo)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  h1 { font-size: 2.25rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }
  h3 { font-size: 1.125rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
  ul { color: var(--text-muted); }
  ol { color: var(--text-muted); padding-left: 1.25rem; }
</style>
